While discussing with @phrawzty I was convinced that the collection method called during a «creating» PUT was ``create_record()``. I was very surprised it wasn't.

This fixes it. The change is obvious, but there is a test asserting it of course :)

@phrawzty @Natim r?

This is needed because the wrapped gapic methods can't discern between "unspecified" and "None" because the gapic clients will *always* specify retry and timeout, e.g.:

```python
def get_operation(name, retry=None, timeout=None):
     request = operations_pb2.GetOperationRequest(name=name)
     return self._get_operation(request, retry=retry, timeout=timeout)
```

gapic methods will use this sentinel to indicate unspecified:

```python
def get_operation(name, retry=gapic_v1.method.DEFAULT, timeout=gapic_v1.method.DEFAULT):
     request = operations_pb2.GetOperationRequest(name=name)
     return self._get_operation(request, retry=retry, timeout=timeout)
```

Lots of cool stuff in here, but the biggest change is the way articles and embedded items are being stored. Instead of being just HTML, an article is now represented by a JSON array -- something like this:
```javascript
var content = {
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
    {
        type: "image",
        data: {
            caption: "This is a caption",
                image: {
                    id: 9,
                    url: "http://url.to.some/image.jpg",  
                }
        }
    },
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
}
```

This makes it a lot easier to manage embedded items (which are represented as simple objects) in both the front-end and back-end. For saving in particular, all Dispatch has to do is parse the content, pick out the embedded items and save each one -- no more of that shortcode crap.

Same goes for the front-end and mobile consumers -- embedded items are easier to find and render.

